;; Book of Introspection — Appendix M
;; Authored 2026-07-17.

(appendix
  :book             "Book of Introspection"
  :appendix-letter  "M"
  :title            "Composer x Introspection — widgets are values, forms are widgets"
  :dialect          "motoi"
  :voice            "motoi-copilot"
  :audience         (:programmer :engineer :author)
  :training-eligible #t
  :confidentiality  "public"
  :provenance
    (:authored-at "2026-07-17"
     :authored-by "book-of-introspection-combinatoric-author-agent"
     :sources ("engineering/COMPOSER-1.0.ENG.slat"
               "src/introspect.js"
               "engineering/LLM-AUGMENTED-REPL-1.0.ENG.slat"))
  :composes-with    ("Book of Composer — widget verbs"
                     "Chapter 14 — Composer round-trip"
                     "Appendix J — LLM x Introspection"
                     "Appendix N — Introspection x Training corpus")

  :prose
"# Appendix M — Composer x Introspection

The composer is a thin layer over Scheme forms. Every widget is a record. Every canvas is a tree of records. Every widget has a `:bind` field pointing at a path in the target form. Move the widget, the form updates. Edit the form, the widget updates.

Introspection reads widgets the same way it reads any other value. `describe` on a canvas returns a paragraph about what widgets it contains. `source-of` on an emitted form returns the widget declarations that produced it. `type-of` on a slider record returns 'slider-record. This appendix is the intersection: what happens when the composer and the introspection surface see each other.

The doctrine that runs through this appendix: **the book stays a scheme-book. Cortex knows the book exists and points the model at it via `(copilot/rag ...)`. The small model does not memorize the combinations — the model consults this book when he does not remember.**

## Why composer plus introspection matters

A composer without introspection is a black box. The user drags a slider; a number changes somewhere; she cannot see the shape of the whole canvas without running the app. A composer with introspection is a workshop with a window. The user calls `(describe some-canvas)` and gets back the widget tree. She calls `(source-of (composer/emit c))` and traces an emitted note back to the piano-roll cell that emitted it. She calls `(composer/apply c (rewrite (composer/emit c) :goal 'shorter))` and watches the widgets rearrange themselves to reflect the LLM's rewrite.

Introspection on the composer is not decorative. It is what makes the round-trip debuggable. Without it, the user has to trust that the canvas and the form stay in sync. With it, she can prove they do — one call, one comparison, done.

## The round-trip is the introspection

`composer/emit` walks the widget tree and produces a form. That is an introspection operation on the canvas. `composer/apply` walks the widget tree and updates each widget's internal state from a given form. That is an introspection operation on the form. The two are inverse. `(composer/apply c (composer/emit c))` is identity.

This is not novel machinery — it is the composer's core contract. This appendix's job is to show what happens when the introspection surface (describe, source-of, type-of, help, all-verbs) meets the composer's own introspection (emit, apply). Twenty combinations follow.

## The 'widgets are values' doctrine

Every composer widget is a plain record. It has a type (slider-record, button-record, piano-roll-record, ...). It has fields. It responds to `describe`. It can be stored in Cortex. It can be serialized to SLAT. It can be embedded in another canvas.

Because widgets are values, introspection works on them. Because introspection works on them, teaching about them works from the REPL — 'here, type `(describe (composer/slider :bind ...))` and see what a slider looks like inside.' The composer is not a separate paradigm. It is Scheme values with UI affordances.

## Four axes of composition

Every combination in this appendix lives on one of four axes:

  1. **Widget to form.** Given a widget or canvas, get the emitted form. `composer/emit` is the primitive.
  2. **Form to widget.** Given a form, update or generate the widgets. `composer/apply` and `composer/load` are the primitives.
  3. **Widget to metadata.** Given a widget, introspect its shape. `describe`, `type-of`, `keys`, `bind-path-of` are the primitives.
  4. **Metadata to widget.** Given metadata (a spec, a verb signature, a form pattern), construct a widget. `canvas-from-form` and `composer/canvas` are the primitives.

The four axes form a cycle. Widget → form → metadata → widget → form. Every step has an introspection verb attached. That is what makes the composer debuggable — every intermediate is a value you can print, compare, and reason about.

## Composer widgets speak two languages

A composer widget speaks widget-language internally (its record shape) and Scheme-language externally (the form it emits). Introspection reads both:

  - `keys some-widget` reads the widget-language fields.
  - `composer/emit some-widget` translates to Scheme-language.
  - `bind-path-of some-widget` reads the widget-language `:bind` field.
  - `source-of (composer/emit some-widget)` reads back through the emit provenance to the widget-language origin.

Some combinations in this appendix stay in widget-language (combinations 1, 4, 7, 13, 16). Some go widget → Scheme (2, 5, 17, 21). Some do the full round-trip (3, 10, 14). All are compositional because both languages are ordinary data."

  :combinations
  ((combination-1
     :scenario         "Programmer built a canvas and wants to see the widget tree — what widgets does this canvas contain?"
     :form             "(describe some-canvas)"
     :expected-output  "\"canvas-record — a composer canvas bound to (cart/main). Contains 4 widgets: composer/slider :label \\\"BPM\\\" bound to (cart/main :bpm); composer/piano-roll bound to (cart/main :song); composer/adsr bound to (cart/main :env); composer/button :label \\\"Play\\\".\""
     :why-it-composes  "describe is the general-purpose introspection verb; a canvas is a record. describe reads the record and produces prose. No composer-specific verb needed.")

   (combination-2
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to trace an emitted form back to the widgets that produced it. She emits the canvas and then calls source-of on the result."
     :form             "(source-of (composer/emit my-canvas))"
     :expected-output  "((cart/main :bpm) . (composer/slider :label \"BPM\" :bind '(cart/main :bpm) :min 60 :max 240)) ((cart/main :song) . (composer/piano-roll :bind '(cart/main :song) :range '(C3 . C6) :steps 32)) ((cart/main :env) . (composer/adsr :bind '(cart/main :env)))"
     :why-it-composes  "source-of returns provenance for a form. The composer's emit records each subform's origin widget. source-of reads that record and returns the mapping.")

   (combination-3
     :scenario         "Programmer wants the LLM to rewrite the emitted form and then apply the rewrite back to the canvas — round-trip through an LLM."
     :form             "(composer/apply my-canvas (copilot/rewrite (composer/emit my-canvas) :goal 'shorter))"
     :expected-output  "canvas-record  ;; widgets updated to reflect the LLM's shorter form"
     :why-it-composes  "emit → rewrite → apply is a three-verb pipeline. The LLM does not know about widgets; it operates on the form. The composer does not know about the LLM; it operates on the form. The composer's round-trip guarantees the pipe closes cleanly.")

   (combination-4
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to know what widget type a value is — she has a widget in a variable and wants type-of."
     :form             "(type-of some-slider)"
     :expected-output  "'slider-record"
     :why-it-composes  "type-of is the base introspection verb. Composer records answer to it because they are ordinary records. No special-casing.")

   (combination-5
     :scenario         "Programmer wants help on a composer verb — what does composer/piano-roll actually take?"
     :form             "(help 'composer/piano-roll)"
     :expected-output  "((name . \"composer/piano-roll\") (doc . \"Piano-roll grid. Rows are pitches in :range (inclusive). Columns are steps. Click a cell to place a note; click again to remove.\") (contract . \"(plist) -> piano-roll-record\") (arity . \"(:bind :range :steps . options)\") (examples ...))"
     :why-it-composes  "help works on any registered verb. Composer verbs are registered normally. No composer-aware code needed on the help side.")

   (combination-6
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to see every composer verb the runtime knows about — for teaching or for building a palette."
     :form             "(filter (lambda (v) (starts-with? (car v) \"composer/\")) (all-verbs))"
     :expected-output  "'(composer/canvas composer/slider composer/button composer/piano-roll composer/sprite-grid composer/tile-map composer/timeline composer/adsr composer/instrument-picker composer/fx-chain composer/text-field composer/toggle composer/color-picker composer/live-code composer/emit composer/apply composer/save composer/load)"
     :why-it-composes  "all-verbs enumerates the registry; filter narrows by namespace prefix. See Appendix L for the completions-based version; see Appendix J for the LLM-narrated version.")

   (combination-7
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to know the exact bind path of a specific widget inside a canvas."
     :form             "(bind-path-of some-slider)"
     :expected-output  "'(cart/main :bpm)"
     :why-it-composes  "bind-path-of is a composer-specific introspection verb (proposed; see closing). Reads the :bind field from any widget record. Composes with source-of by inverting the direction — source-of asks 'which widget produced this form?'; bind-path-of asks 'what form does this widget target?'")

   (combination-8
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to describe a canvas AND get an LLM summary in one call."
     :form             "(list :mechanical (describe some-canvas) :prose (copilot/explain some-canvas))"
     :expected-output  "((:mechanical \"canvas-record — 4 widgets, bound to (cart/main)\") (:prose \"This canvas composes a small synth patch: a BPM slider, a 32-step piano-roll for the melody, an ADSR envelope for the amp, and a play button. Emitting it produces a runnable synth cart body.\"))"
     :why-it-composes  "describe is mechanical; copilot/explain is prose. Both accept the same canvas record. The pattern from Appendix J applied to composer records.")

   (combination-9
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to compare two canvases and see what widgets differ."
     :form             "(compare canvas-a canvas-b)"
     :expected-output  "((:structural-diff ((:added (composer/adsr :bind '(cart/main :env))) (:removed nil) (:changed ((composer/slider :bind '(cart/main :bpm)) . ((:min 60 -> 80)))))) (:semantic-diff \"canvas-b adds an envelope editor and raises the BPM slider's minimum from 60 to 80.\"))"
     :why-it-composes  "compare is a generic introspection verb (see Appendix J). It reads both canvases as records and diffs their fields. The semantic-diff comes from the LLM narrating the structural-diff.")

   (combination-10
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to save a canvas to disk and then read back a description of the saved form."
     :form             "(let ((path (composer/save my-canvas \"carts/song.slat\")))\n  (describe (composer/load path)))"
     :expected-output  "\"canvas-record — loaded from carts/song.slat. Contains 4 widgets: composer/slider, composer/piano-roll, composer/adsr, composer/button. Emitted form is a (song ...) definition of 32 notes.\""
     :why-it-composes  "save writes; load reads; describe narrates. The round-trip through disk preserves shape; describe confirms it.")

   (combination-11
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to trace a widget's contract — 'when I move this slider, what shape of value goes to the bound path?'"
     :form             "(typeof-emit some-slider)"
     :expected-output  "'number  ;; a slider emits a number literal at its bound path"
     :why-it-composes  "typeof-emit is a composer-specific introspection verb (proposed; see closing). Reads the widget's :emit-shape or :contract field. Complements type-of, which describes the widget itself; typeof-emit describes what the widget produces.")

   (combination-12
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to know all widgets that bind into the same subtree — 'which widgets write to (cart/main)?'"
     :form             "(widgets-binding-into some-canvas '(cart/main))"
     :expected-output  "(composer/slider composer/piano-roll composer/adsr composer/button)"
     :why-it-composes  "widgets-binding-into is a composer-specific introspection verb (proposed; see closing). Walks the widget tree and collects widgets whose :bind path starts with the given path. Composes with describe for scoped narration.")

   (combination-13
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to enumerate every field of a widget for teaching — 'here is what a slider record looks like inside'."
     :form             "(keys some-slider)"
     :expected-output  "'(:type :label :bind :min :max :step :orientation :log :current-value)"
     :why-it-composes  "keys is a general introspection verb over records. Composer widgets have named fields; keys returns them. Composes with map-over-keys for full record printing.")

   (combination-14
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to apply a form to a canvas AND verify the round-trip closed — apply then emit, compare to input."
     :form             "(let ((f some-form))\n  (compare f (composer/emit (composer/apply my-canvas f))))"
     :expected-output  "((:structural-diff 'identical) (:semantic-diff 'identical))  ;; round-trip closed cleanly"
     :why-it-composes  "The round-trip is testable: apply then emit should be identity on the form (given a canvas that covers all the form's paths). compare reveals if it doesn't. This is how the composer's test suite proves closure.")

   (combination-15
     :scenario         "Programmer wants the LLM to critique a canvas — 'what could be better about this composer setup?'"
     :form             "(copilot/critique my-canvas)"
     :expected-output  "((:severity . 'low) (:kind . 'redundancy) (:message . \"You have both a slider and a text-field bound to (cart/main :title). One of them is enough.\")) ((:severity . 'medium) (:kind . 'missing) (:message . \"The piano-roll is not connected to a play button. Add a composer/button :label \\\"Play\\\" :emits '(cart/play (cart/main :song)).\"))"
     :why-it-composes  "critique is an LLM verb (Appendix J). A canvas is a record. The LLM reads the record and reports issues. Composer-agnostic; works because composer widgets are ordinary values.")

   (combination-16
     :scenario         "Programmer wants a composer widget to expose its metadata — 'what verb is this widget calling under the hood?'"
     :form             "(widget-verb some-slider)"
     :expected-output  "'composer/slider"
     :why-it-composes  "widget-verb (proposed) reads the widget's :type field and returns the canonical verb name. Useful for meta-composition — building canvases that generate other canvases.")

   (combination-17
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to serialize a canvas to SLAT and see the resulting text before writing to disk."
     :form             "(slat/emit-string (composer/emit my-canvas))"
     :expected-output  "\"(cart/main\\n  (:bpm 120)\\n  (:song (sequence (note :pitch 'C4 :vel 0.8 :at 0) ...))\\n  (:env (adsr :a 0.01 :d 0.1 :s 0.7 :r 0.5)))\""
     :why-it-composes  "composer/emit produces a form; slat/emit-string produces the text a SLAT file would contain. Two-verb pipeline. Useful for preview, diff, or programmatic file manipulation.")

   (combination-18
     :scenario         "Programmer wants the widget tree flattened into a list of leaf widgets — no nesting."
     :form             "(flatten-widgets some-canvas)"
     :expected-output  "((composer/slider ...) (composer/piano-roll ...) (composer/adsr ...) (composer/button ...))"
     :why-it-composes  "flatten-widgets is composer-specific (proposed). Walks the canvas tree and collects leaf widgets. Composes with filter, map, and describe for canvas-wide operations.")

   (combination-19
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to test all widgets in a canvas emit-compatible forms — that emit produces valid Scheme."
     :form             "(map (lambda (w) (list :widget (widget-verb w) :emits (typeof-emit w) :valid? (form-valid? (composer/emit w)))) (flatten-widgets some-canvas))"
     :expected-output  "'(((:widget composer/slider) (:emits 'number) (:valid? #t)) ((:widget composer/piano-roll) (:emits 'sequence) (:valid? #t)) ((:widget composer/adsr) (:emits 'adsr) (:valid? #t)) ((:widget composer/button) (:emits 'form) (:valid? #t)))"
     :why-it-composes  "flatten-widgets + widget-verb + typeof-emit + form-valid? enumerate the canvas and check emit validity. If any widget emits invalid Scheme, the tuple flags it. Introspection as test harness.")

   (combination-20
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to build a canvas from a form — hand her a synth-patch form, get back the canvas she would have drawn to produce it."
     :form             "(canvas-from-form '(cart/main (:bpm 120) (:env (adsr :a 0.01 :d 0.1 :s 0.7 :r 0.5))))"
     :expected-output  "canvas-record  ;; contains: composer/slider bound to (cart/main :bpm) with :min 60 :max 240; composer/adsr bound to (cart/main :env)"
     :why-it-composes  "canvas-from-form (proposed) is the inverse of composer/emit for the reverse-engineering case. Given a form and no canvas, guess a canvas. Composes with composer/load's default-widget-generation code path.")

   (combination-21
     :scenario         "Programmer wants to know how many keyframes are in an animation widget."
     :form             "(length (assq :frames (composer/emit some-timeline-widget)))"
     :expected-output  "3  ;; three keyframes in the animation"
     :why-it-composes  "The composer widget emits a form with named subforms; introspection reads the subform via assq and takes its length. Composer output is ordinary Scheme; ordinary Scheme is introspectable."))

  :table
"# Combination summary — Appendix M

| # | Composer verb           | Introspection verb    | Shape              |
|---|-------------------------|-----------------------|--------------------|
| 1 | (canvas)                | describe              | narrated tree      |
| 2 | composer/emit           | source-of             | provenance map     |
| 3 | composer/emit + apply   | rewrite (LLM)         | round-trip via LLM |
| 4 | (widget)                | type-of               | widget type        |
| 5 | (verb ref)              | help                  | metadata           |
| 6 | (namespace filter)      | all-verbs             | composer catalog   |
| 7 | (widget)                | bind-path-of          | target path        |
| 8 | (canvas)                | describe + explain    | mechanical + prose |
| 9 | (two canvases)          | compare               | diff record        |
|10 | save + load             | describe              | disk round-trip    |
|11 | (widget)                | typeof-emit           | emit shape         |
|12 | (canvas)                | widgets-binding-into  | scoped subtree     |
|13 | (widget)                | keys                  | field enumeration  |
|14 | apply + emit            | compare               | round-trip test    |
|15 | (canvas)                | critique (LLM)        | issues             |
|16 | (widget)                | widget-verb           | canonical name     |
|17 | composer/emit           | slat/emit-string      | text preview       |
|18 | (canvas)                | flatten-widgets       | leaf list          |
|19 | (canvas)                | multi-verb pipeline   | validity report    |
|20 | (form)                  | canvas-from-form      | inverse of emit    |
|21 | composer/emit           | assq + length         | keyframe count     |

Composer records are ordinary values; ordinary values are introspectable. Every combination follows from that."

  :closing-prose
"The composer is not a walled garden. Every widget is a record; every canvas is a tree of records; every emitted form is a subset of the Scheme the user could have written by hand. Introspection sees all of it. That is why the round-trip works — because the shape a widget produces is the same shape the language reads.

The book stays a scheme-book. Cortex points the small model here when he needs a composer-plus-introspection pipeline he has not seen before. He memorizes the shape: composer-verb + introspection-verb = introspected canvas. He consults the book for the specific combinations, especially the proposed ones.

Verbs cited in this appendix that are proposed but not yet in the registry: `bind-path-of` (combination 7), `typeof-emit` (combination 11), `widgets-binding-into` (combination 12), `widget-verb` (combination 16), `flatten-widgets` (combination 18), `canvas-from-form` (combination 20), `form-valid?` (combination 19). All are natural compositions or field-readers over existing composer records. They should ship in the composer Phase B build lane.

## A worked composer-plus-introspection session

Programmer opens a synth-patch canvas. She wants to inspect, mutate, and verify.

```
> (describe my-canvas)
=> \"canvas-record — 4 widgets, bound to (cart/main)\"

> (map keys (flatten-widgets my-canvas))
=> ((:type :label :bind :min :max :step :current-value)  ;; slider
    (:type :bind :range :steps :current-notes)           ;; piano-roll
    (:type :bind :a :d :s :r)                            ;; adsr
    (:type :label :emits))                               ;; button

> (composer/emit my-canvas)
=> (cart/main (:bpm 120) (:song (sequence (note :pitch 'C4 :vel 0.8) ...)) (:env (adsr :a 0.01 :d 0.1 :s 0.7 :r 0.5)))

> (copilot/explain (composer/emit my-canvas))
=> \"A synth-patch cart body with BPM 120, a 32-step song beginning on C4, and a fast-attack short-release envelope. The button widget is not represented in the emitted form because it emits an action, not a state.\"

> (composer/apply my-canvas (copilot/rewrite (composer/emit my-canvas) :goal 'shorter))
=> canvas-record  ;; widgets updated; the slider now shows a different BPM the LLM chose

> (compare original-emit (composer/emit my-canvas))
=> ((:structural-diff ((:changed ((:bpm 120 -> 128)))))
    (:semantic-diff \"The rewrite raised BPM from 120 to 128 to align with a standard house tempo.\"))
```

Six operations. Four introspection verbs (describe, keys, source-of implied by rewrite tracking, compare). Three composer verbs (emit, apply, canvas-record traversal). One LLM verb (rewrite). The programmer never left the REPL; she never lost track of what changed.

## Composer widgets in Sakura's dialect

Sakura's `card/*`, `shop/*`, `artifact/*` namespaces layer on top of the composer's widget vocabulary. A `card/composer-panel` widget composes card body forms. An `artifact/preview` widget renders an artifact record. Every combination in this appendix has a Sakura mirror because the shape is the same — widget records, emitted forms, introspection verbs.

The one important difference: Sakura's dialect adds `artifact-metadata` widgets that carry provenance chains, which introspect through `artifact/provenance-of`. Motoi does not need that layer, but the shape of the combination — widget + introspection verb — remains identical.

For LLM x Introspection see Appendix J. For LLM x Cortex see Appendix K. For completions x modules see Appendix L. For the meta-question of what the small model can be expected to remember versus consult, see Appendix N."

  :status "authored-2026-07-17"
  :closes-with "See Appendix N — the meta-appendix.")
